TY  - JOUR
AU  - Aghion, Philippe
AU  - Algan, Yann
AU  - Cahuc, Pierre
AU  - Shleifer, Andrei
T1  - Regulation and Distrust*
PY  - 2010
Y1  - 2010/08/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.2010.125.3.1015
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 125
IS  - 3
SP  - 1015
EP  - 1049
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We document that, in a cross section of countries, government regulation is strongly negatively correlated with measures of trust. In a simple model explaining this correlation, distrust creates public demand for regulation, whereas regulation in turn discourages formation of trust, leading to multiple equilibria. A key implication of the model is that individuals in low-trust countries want more government intervention even though they know the government is corrupt. We test this and other implications of the model using country- and individual-level data on trust and beliefs about the role of government, as well as on changes in beliefs during the transition from socialism.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.2010.125.3.1015
ER  - 



